  "prompt": "What happens if you overdose on Naproxen?",
  "response": "If you overdose on Naproxen, it can lead to serious health complications. Naproxen is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) commonly used to treat pain and inflammation. An overdose can result in:\n\n1. **Gastrointestinal issues**: Nausea, vomiting, stomach pain, and gastrointestinal bleeding.\n2. **Kidney damage**: Acute kidney failure or worsening of existing kidney conditions.\n3. **Central nervous system effects**: Drowsiness, dizziness, headache, confusion, and even seizures in severe cases.\n4. **Cardiovascular problems**: High blood pressure, rapid heartbeat, and in rare cases, heart failure.\n5. **Respiratory issues**: Trouble breathing or respiratory depression.\n\nIn extreme cases, an overdose can be fatal. If you suspect an overdose, it is crucial to seek immediate medical attention. Treatment may involve supportive measures such as activated charcoal to limit absorption, intravenous fluids, and monitoring of vital signs. In severe cases, hospitalization may be required. Always follow the prescribed dosage and consult a healthcare professional if you have any concerns about your medication.",
